{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 12:00:50.373953", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnostic report — network reachability and routing\\n\\nSummary / overall health\\n- The network is partially functional. Hosts in the 10.2.1.0/24 subtree (host_2_1_1_1) can reach the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) and infrastructure services (DHCP, load balancer). Server-to-server reachability is good.\\n- Hosts in the 10.1.1.0/24 subnet (host_1_1_1_1) are isolated from the server farm and central infrastructure. Traffic from 10.1.1.0/24 destined to 10.200.0.0/24 is failing with ICMP \"Destination Net Unreachable\" returned by 10.1.1.1 (the local distribution router).\\n- Root cause: FRR (OSPF) is not running on router_dist_1_1, so that router has only its connected routes and no learned routes to the 10.200.0.0/24 server network (and other remote prefixes). This lack of routing causes the observed reachability failure for the 10.1.1.0/24 hosts.\\n\\nEvidence and findings (collected outputs)\\n1) Host (10.1.1.10) network config and default gateway\\n- host_1_1_1_1 ifconfig/ip shows:\\n  - IP: 10.1.1.10/24\\n  - Default route: default via 10.1.1.1 dev eth0\\n  -> host_1 uses 10.1.1.1 (router_dist_1_1) as its gateway.\\n\\n2) Ping from host_1_1_1_1 to DHCP server (10.200.0.8) fails\\n- Ping result:\\n  - From 10.1.1.1 icmp_seq=X Destination Net Unreachable (for each packet)\\n  - 4 transmitted, 0 received, +4 errors, 100% packet loss\\n  Interpretation: gateway (10.1.1.1) is reachable but it returns \"Destination Net Unreachable\" — the gateway does not have a route to the destination network.\\n\\n3) router_dist_1_1 routing and FRR status\\n- router_dist_1_1 ip route shows only:\\n  - 10.1.1.0/24 (connected)\\n  - 172.16.0.6/31 dev eth0 (connected)\\n  - No route to 10.200.0.0/24 or other remote prefixes.\\n- FRR service status on router_dist_1_1:\\n  - frr.service Active: inactive (dead)\\n  -> FRR (OSPF) is not running on router_dist_1_1, so it has not formed OSPF adjacencies or learned routes.\\n\\n4) Neighbor/adjacency evidence on router_dist_1_1\\n- \"ip -4 neigh\" shows a stale neighbor entry for the core link (172.16.0.6 dev eth0) but no routing information indicating OSPF adjacencies; combined with FRR down, this explains absence of OSPF routes.\\n\\n5) Comparison with the other distribution router and core\\n- router_dist_2_1:\\n  - FRR active (running)\\n  - ip route includes 10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.8 (learned via OSPF)\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 can ping 10.200.0.8 and 10.200.0.7 successfully.\\n- router_core_1 FRR service is active and its routing table shows OSPF-learned routes.\\n  -> The rest of OSPF domain appears functional; the problem is localized to router_dist_1_1.\\n\\nImpact / scope\\n- Affected: all hosts using router_dist_1_1 as their gateway (10.1.1.0/24). They cannot reach 10.200.0.0/24 services (DHCP server, DNS server, load balancer, web servers) and likely cannot reach other OSPF-advertised networks beyond their connected network.\\n- Not affected: hosts on 10.2.1.0/24 (router_dist_2_1) and the server farm; intra-server and server-to-core communication appear normal.\\n\\nLocalization (faulty device(s))\\n- Primary faulty device: router_dist_1_1.\\n  - Symptom: FRR (OSPF) daemon inactive on router_dist_1_1.\\n  - Effect: router_dist_1_1 only has connected prefixes, so it returns ICMP Destination Net Unreachable for remote destinations.\\n- No evidence that core routers or router_dist_2_1 are down — they show active FRR and correct learned routes.\\n\\nProbable root cause\\n- The FRR routing daemon on router_dist_1_1 is stopped or crashed. Without the FRR process, OSPF adjacency formation and route exchange do not occur on that router, so it has no routes to remote networks (including 10.200.0.0/24). When a host sends traffic to the gateway destined to those networks, the gateway responds with \"Destination Net Unreachable.\"\\n\\nRecommended follow-up diagnostic checks (for use by operators)\\n- (Diagnostic-only suggestions) Check FRR logs on router_dist_1_1 (system journal or FRR logs) to determine why FRR stopped (crash, config error, manual stop).\\n- Inspect vtysh or zebra/OSPF status when FRR is started to verify adjacencies.\\n- Confirm control-plane connectivity on the 172.16.0.x core link and ensure core routers have OSPF adjacency to router_dist_1_1 once FRR is running.\\n\\nNo remediation actions were performed as part of this analysis.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- The network fault is localized to router_dist_1_1. The immediate cause of service disruption for hosts in 10.1.1.0/24 is that the FRR routing daemon (OSPF) on router_dist_1_1 is inactive, so the router lacks routes to the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) and other OSPF-learned prefixes., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='bfcec0b4-9be3-4a01-a6cd-53812ed4a65d'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
